\pard\qc\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs32 CHAPTER FOUR\b0 \par
\pard\qc\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs32 SYSTEM ANALYSIS\b0 \par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 4.0 Overview\b0 \par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 This chapter presents the system analysis for the proposed Decentralized Academic Credentials Verification system. It examines the feasibility of developing and implementing the system, describes the current system used in academic credential issuance and verification, and highlights the weaknesses that justify the need for the proposed solution.\par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 4.1 Feasibility Study\b0 \par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 A feasibility study is an evaluation carried out to determine whether a proposed system is practical and suitable for implementation within a given environment. For the Decentralized Academic Credentials Verification system, the study focused on technical, economic, operational, legal, and schedule feasibility.\par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 4.1.1 Technical Feasibility\b0 \par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 The system is technically feasible because it can be developed using available web technologies, backend services, databases, and decentralized verification tools. Users can access the platform using internet-enabled computers and smartphones.\par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 4.1.2 Economic Feasibility\b0 \par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 The system is economically feasible because open-source technologies reduce development cost while the platform is expected to reduce verification delays, paperwork, and fraud-related losses.\par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 4.1.3 Operational Feasibility\b0 \par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 The system is operationally feasible because it addresses real needs of institutions, students, employers, and administrators. User training will still be important for successful adoption.\par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 4.1.4 Legal Feasibility\b0 \par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 The system is legally feasible provided access control, privacy, and institutional data governance requirements are observed during deployment and use.\par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 4.1.5 Schedule Feasibility\b0 \par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 The project is schedule-feasible because development can be completed in phases including planning, analysis, design, implementation, testing, and documentation within the academic timeline.\par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 Table 4.1: Summary of Feasibility Study\b0 \par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 - Technical | Technology and expertise availability | System can be built using available tools | Feasible\par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 - Economic | Cost versus benefit | Open-source tools reduce cost | Feasible\par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 - Operational | Ability to work in real environment | Stakeholders can use the system with training | Feasible\par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 - Legal | Compliance with rules and policy | Requires access control and privacy protection | Feasible\par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 - Schedule | Ability to finish in time | Work can be completed in phases | Feasible\par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 4.2 Description of Current System\b0 \par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 The current system used for academic credential issuance and verification is largely manual or based on isolated centralized processes. Academic certificates are usually printed, signed, and physically issued to students, while verification is carried out through phone calls, letters, or email communication with the issuing institution.\par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 4.2.1 Functional Components of the Current System\b0 \par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 - Certificate preparation by the academic institution.\par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 - Manual approval, signing, stamping, and printing.\par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 - Physical issuance of the certificate to the student.\par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 - Storage of duplicate records in files or institutional databases.\par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 - Manual verification by employers or other institutions.\par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 - Administrative follow-up by institutional staff.\par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 4.2.2 Weaknesses of the Current System\b0 \par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 The current system is slow, susceptible to forgery, difficult to track, and does not provide a common trusted platform for instant verification.\par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 Table 4.2: Weaknesses of the Current System\b0 \par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 - Certificate issuance | Manual printing and signing | Time-consuming | Delays in receiving credentials\par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 - Record storage | Physical files or isolated databases | Risk of loss and inconsistency | Difficult retrieval of records\par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 - Verification | Calls, emails, letters | Slow and unreliable | Delayed decisions\par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 - Fraud detection | Manual inspection | Weak detection capability | Fake certificates may pass\par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 - Revocation tracking | Manual follow-up | Poor visibility | Invalid credentials may still circulate\par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 4.3 Summary of System Analysis\b0 \par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 The system analysis established that the proposed Decentralized Academic Credentials Verification system is feasible and necessary. The analysis of the current system revealed major weaknesses including slow verification, weak fraud control, manual record handling, and limited transparency. These challenges justify the development of a decentralized system capable of providing secure, efficient, and trusted academic credential verification.\par
\pard\qc\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 Figure 4.1: Existing Manual Academic Credential Issuance and Verification Process\b0 \par
\pard\qc\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs32 CHAPTER FIVE\b0 \par
\pard\qc\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs32 SYSTEM DESIGN\b0 \par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 5.0 Overview\b0 \par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 This chapter presents the design of the proposed Decentralized Academic Credentials Verification system. It describes the proposed system, outlines its functional and non-functional requirements, and presents the logical and physical design of the system.\par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 5.1 Description of the Proposed System\b0 \par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 The proposed system is a web-based decentralized platform for issuing, managing, sharing, and verifying academic credentials. It enables institutions to issue secure digital credentials, allows students to access and manage their credentials, and gives employers the ability to verify credentials quickly and reliably.\par
\pard\qc\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 Figure 5.1: Home Page of the Proposed System\b0 \par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 5.2 Functional Requirements of the Proposed System\b0 \par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 5.2.1 User Authentication and Access Control\b0 \par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 The system shall support secure login, role assignment, and restricted access based on user permissions.\par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 5.2.2 Institution Functions\b0 \par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 The system shall support institution onboarding, credential issuance, credential revocation, student management, and bulk import.\par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 5.2.3 Student Functions\b0 \par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 The system shall allow students to view, claim, share, and manage privacy settings for their credentials.\par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 5.2.4 Employer and Verifier Functions\b0 \par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 The system shall support single and bulk credential verification and display clear verification outcomes.\par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 5.2.5 Administrative Functions\b0 \par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 The system shall support approval workflows, monitoring, analytics, and audit review.\par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 5.2.6 Interface Requirements\b0 \par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 The interface shall validate input correctly and provide clear navigation and feedback messages.\par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 5.2.7 Business Requirements\b0 \par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 Required data must be provided before credential issuance and only authorized roles may perform key operations.\par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 5.2.8 Regulatory and Compliance Requirements\b0 \par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 The system shall maintain audit trails and restrict access to authorized users only.\par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 5.2.9 Security Requirements\b0 \par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 The system shall enforce role-based access control and log critical operations.\par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 Table 5.1: Functional Requirements of the Proposed System\b0 \par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 - FR1 | Support user login and authentication | All users | High\par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 - FR2 | Enforce role-based access control | All users | High\par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 - FR3 | Allow institution onboarding | Institution/Admin | High\par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 - FR4 | Allow credential issuance | Institution Admin | High\par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 - FR5 | Allow credential revocation | Institution Admin | High\par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 - FR6 | Allow students to claim credentials | Student | High\par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 - FR7 | Allow students to share credentials | Student | High\par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 - FR8 | Allow single credential verification | Employer | High\par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 - FR9 | Support bulk verification | Employer | Medium\par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 5.3 Non-Functional Requirements of the Proposed System\b0 \par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 5.3.1 Performance Requirements\b0 \par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 The system should return results quickly during normal verification and dashboard use.\par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 5.3.2 Security Requirements\b0 \par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 The system should protect data through authentication, authorization, and audit logging.\par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 5.3.3 Usability Requirements\b0 \par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 The interface should be easy to learn and use.\par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 5.3.4 Reliability Requirements\b0 \par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 The system should provide accurate and dependable verification results.\par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 5.3.5 Scalability Requirements\b0 \par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 The system should support future growth in users and records.\par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 5.3.6 Maintainability Requirements\b0 \par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 The system should be modular and easy to update.\par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 5.3.7 Availability Requirements\b0 \par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 The system should remain accessible whenever users need it.\par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 5.3.8 Data Integrity Requirements\b0 \par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 The system should preserve correctness and consistency of credential records.\par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 5.3.9 Interoperability Requirements\b0 \par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 The system should interact effectively with supporting services and platforms.\par
\pard\ql\sl480\slmult1 \b \f0\fs24 Table 5.2: Non-Functional Requirements\b0 \par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 - Performance | Fast system response | Improves efficiency\par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 - Security | Protects credentials and user data | Critical\par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 - Usability | Easy to learn and use | Supports adoption\par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 - Reliability | Accurate and dependable results | Builds trust\par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 - Scalability | Supports future growth | Long-term benefit\par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 - Maintainability | Easy to update and improve | Supports future work\par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 - Availability | Accessible when needed | Ensures continuity\par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 - Data Integrity | Correct and consistent records | Prevents misinformation\par
\pard\qj\sl480\slmult1 \f0\fs24 - Interoperability | Works with other services | Enables integration\par
